No

**Describe the solution you'd like**
The CloudFormation resource `AWS::MWAA::Environment`  (Managed Workflows for Apache Airflows) includes multiple properties that could be supported by the package command. These are split across one property to specify an S3 bucket and multiple object keys in that bucket for use by the service.
These files could be uploaded by the `aws cloudformation package` command.

* "DagS3Path",
* "PluginsS3Path" ,
* "RequirementsS3Path",

The resource type also supports the specification of S3 Object version for resources. These might need to be handled by the package command

**Describe alternatives you've considered**
None

**Additional context**
[`AWS:MWAA::Environment` - CloudFormation Docs](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/aws-resource-mwaa-environment.html)', 'reactions': {'url': *Description of changes:*
Vendor the `witch.js` helper

`witch.js` is a lambda layer that performs some magic to upload the web site contents.
Previously it was provided as a external lambda layer. This PR adds the layer definition to the repository.

## Testing

- [X] Run the updated `publish.sh` script successfully
- [X] Deploy the updated template
- [X] Verify the website contents

*Description of changes:*
Vendor the `witch.js` helper

`witch.js` is a lambda layer that performs some magic to upload the web site contents.
Previously it was provided as a external lambda layer. This PR adds the layer definition to the repository.

## Testing

- [X] Run the updated `publish.sh` script successfully
- [X] Deploy the updated template
- [X] Verify the website contents

*Description of changes:*
Vendor the `witch.js` helper

`witch.js` is a lambda layer that performs some magic to upload the web site contents.
Previously it was provided as a external lambda layer. This PR adds the layer definition to the repository.

## Testing

- [X] Run the updated `publish.sh` script successfully
- [X] Deploy the updated template
- [X] Verify the website contents

*Description of changes:*
Vendor the `witch.js` helper

`witch.js` is a lambda layer that performs some magic to upload the web site contents.
Previously it was provided as a external lambda layer. This PR adds the layer definition to the repository.

## Testing

- [X] Run the updated `publish.sh` script successfully
- [X] Deploy the updated template
- [X] Verify the website contents

*Description of changes:*
Vendor the `witch.js` helper

`witch.js` is a lambda layer that performs some magic to upload the web site contents.
Previously it was provided as a external lambda layer. This PR adds the layer definition to the repository.

## Testing

- [X] Run the updated `publish.sh` script successfully
- [X] Deploy the updated template
- [X] Verify the website contents

*Description of changes:*
Vendor the `witch.js` helper

`witch.js` is a lambda layer that performs some magic to upload the web site contents.
Previously it was provided as a external lambda layer. This PR adds the layer definition to the repository.

## Testing

- [X] Run the updated `publish.sh` script successfully
- [X] Deploy the updated template
- [X] Verify the website contents

*Description of changes:*
Vendor the `witch.js` helper

`witch.js` is a lambda layer that performs some magic to upload the web site contents.
Previously it was provided as a external lambda layer. This PR adds the layer definition to the repository.

## Testing

- [X] Run the updated `publish.sh` script successfully
- [X] Deploy the updated template
- [X] Verify the website contents

Vendor the `witch.js` helper

Thanks for opening an issue.

The default [content security policy](https://content-security-policy.com/) of the sample will block external scripts from being run by the browser. This is why you have received this error.

The content security policy is added by a CloudFront response headers policy included in the template. You can update this policy in https://github.com/aws-samples/amazon-cloudfront-secure-static-site/blob/77d1971b6f1a22ef0bb5f5df5550ca507f727672/templates/cloudfront-site.yaml#L146

*Description of changes:*
This PR improves local development. I have introduced Makefile to create virtual environment and install tools such as pre-commit, bum2version and more. Furthermore the whole local development set up has been documented to bring all the contributors on the same environment set up.


*Testing*
The Makefile and the commands has been tested on following operating systems:

- macOS 12.2 Monterey
- Ubuntu 20.4 running on Windows1 0 WSL1

*Description of changes:*
This PR improves local development. I have introduced Makefile to create virtual environment and install tools such as pre-commit, bum2version and more. Furthermore the whole local development set up has been documented to bring all the contributors on the same environment set up.


*Testing*
The Makefile and the commands has been tested on following operating systems:

- macOS 12.2 Monterey
- Ubuntu 20.4 running on Windows1 0 WSL1

*Testing*
The Makefile and the commands has been tested on following operating systems:

- Ubuntu 20.4 running on Windows1 0 WSL1

*Description of changes:*
This PR improves local development. I have introduced Makefile to create virtual environment and install tools such as pre-commit, bum2version and more. Furthermore the whole local development set up has been documented to bring all the contributors on the same environment set up.


*Testing*
The Makefile and the commands has been tested on following operating systems:

- macOS 12.2 Monterey
- Ubuntu 20.4 running on Windows1 0 WSL1

*Description of changes:*
This PR improves local development. I have introduced Makefile to create virtual environment and install tools such as pre-commit, bum2version and more. Furthermore the whole local development set up has been documented to bring all the contributors on the same environment set up.


*Testing*
The Makefile and the commands has been tested on following operating systems:

- Ubuntu 20.4 running on Windows1 0 WSL1

*Description of changes:*
This PR improves local development. I have introduced Makefile to create virtual environment and install tools such as pre-commit, bum2version and more. Furthermore the whole local development set up has been documented to bring all the contributors on the same environment set up.


*Testing*
The Makefile and the commands has been tested on following operating systems:

- macOS 12.2 Monterey
- Ubuntu 20.4 running on Windows1 0 WSL1

*Description of changes:*
This PR improves local development. I have introduced Makefile to create virtual environment and install tools such as pre-commit, bum2version and more. Furthermore the whole local development set up has been documented to bring all the contributors on the same environment set up.


*Testing*
The Makefile and the commands has been tested on following operating systems:

- macOS 12.2 Monterey
- Ubuntu 20.4 running on Windows1 0 WSL1
